[
  {
    "type": "EXPOSITORY (ENGLISH BIBLE)",
    "name": "Matthew Henry's Concise Commentary",
    "elements": [
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "16:1-4 The Pharisees and Sadducees were opposed to each other in principles and in conduct; yet they joined against Christ. But they desired a sign of their own choosing: they despised those signs which relieved the necessity of the sick and sorrowful, and called for something else which would gratify the curiosity of the proud. It is great hypocrisy, when we slight the signs of God's ordaining, to seek for signs of our own devising.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "",
        "children": []
      }
    ]
  },
  {
    "type": "EXPOSITORY (ENGLISH BIBLE)",
    "name": "Barnes' Notes on the Bible",
    "elements": [
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "He answered ... - The meaning of this answer is, There are certain indications by which you judge about the weather.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "p",
        "class": "",
        "text": "In the evening you think you can predict the weather tomorrow. You have evidence in the redness of the sky by which you judge. So there are sufficient indications on which you should judge concerning me and these times. My miracles, and the state of affairs in Judea, are an indication by which you should judge.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "p",
        "class": "",
        "text": "Is red - Almost all nations have observed this as an indication of fair weather.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "p",
        "class": "",
        "text": "In the morning ...the sky is red and lowering - That is, there are threatening clouds in the sky, which are made red by the rays of the rising sun. This, in Judea, was a sign of a tempest. In other places, however, the signs of a storm may be different.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "p",
        "class": "",
        "text": "The face of the sky - The appearance of the sky.",
        "children": [
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "",
            "text": "The face of the sky - The appearance of the sky.",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "verse-link",
            "text": "",
            "children": []
          }
        ]
      }
    ]
  },
  {
    "type": "EXPOSITORY (ENGLISH BIBLE)",
    "name": "Jamieson-Fausset-Brown Bible Commentary",
    "elements": [
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "CHAPTER 16",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "p",
        "class": "",
        "text": "Mt 16:1-12. A Sign from Heaven Sought and Refused—Caution against the Leaven of the Pharisees and Sadducees.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "p",
        "class": "",
        "text": "For the exposition, see on [1315]Mr 8:11-21.",
        "children": []
      }
    ]
  },
  {
    "type": "EXPOSITORY (ENGLISH BIBLE)",
    "name": "Matthew Poole's Commentary",
    "elements": [
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "Ver. 2,3. You can, saith our Saviour, make observations upon the works of God in nature and common providence, and from such observations you can make conclusions; if you see the sky red in the evening, you can conclude from thence that the morrow will be fair, because you think that the redness of the sky at night speaks the clouds thin and the air pure; and on the other side, the redness of it in the morning speaks the clouds thick, so as the sun cannot disperse them; or because you observe that generally it so proveth, though nothing be more mutable than the air. But you cannot ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "p",
        "text": "",
        "children": [
          {
            "element": "br",
            "class": "",
            "text": "",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "br",
            "class": "",
            "text": "",
            "children": []
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "bld",
        "text": "discern the signs of the times:",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " you are only dull at making observations upon the Scriptures, and the will of God revealed in them concerning me. You might observe that all the signs of the Messias are fulfilled in me: I was born of a virgin, as was prophesied by Isaiah, ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "bld",
        "text": "Isaiah 7:14",
        "children": [
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "verse-link",
            "text": "Isaiah 7:14",
            "children": []
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "; in Bethlehem Judah, as was prophesied by Micah, ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "bld",
        "text": "Micah 5:2",
        "children": [
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "verse-link",
            "text": "Micah 5:2",
            "children": []
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "; at a time when the sceptre was departed from Judah, and the lawgiver from his feet, as was prophesied by Jacob, ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "bld",
        "text": "Genesis 49:10",
        "children": [
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "verse-link",
            "text": "Genesis 49:10",
            "children": []
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ": that John the Baptist is come in the power and spirit of Elias, to prepare my way before me, as was prophesied by Malachi, ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "bld",
        "text": "Malachi 4:5",
        "children": [
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "verse-link",
            "text": "Malachi 4:5",
            "children": []
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "; that there is one come, who openeth the eyes of the blind, and unstops the ears of the deaf, and maketh the lame to leap as an hart, and the tongue of the dumb to sing, according to the prophecy, ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "bld",
        "text": "Isaiah 35:5,6",
        "children": [
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "verse-link",
            "text": "Isaiah 35:5",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "",
            "text": ",6",
            "children": []
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ". All these are the signs of the time when the Messiah was to come; but these things you cannot discern, but, like a company of hypocrites, who pretend one thing and do another, you come and ask a sign, that you might believe in me, when you have so many, and yet will not believe. ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "p",
        "text": "",
        "children": [
          {
            "element": "br",
            "class": "",
            "text": "",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "br",
            "class": "",
            "text": "",
            "children": []
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "",
        "children": []
      }
    ]
  },
  {
    "type": "EXPOSITORY (ENGLISH BIBLE)",
    "name": "Gill's Exposition of the Entire Bible",
    "elements": [
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "And in the morning, it will be foul weather today,.... When you rise in the morning, and take a survey of the heavens, it is a very usual thing with you to say, it is like to be windy or rainy weather today, ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "p",
        "class": "",
        "text": "for the sky is red and lowring; which shows, that the clouds are so thick that the sun cannot pierce through them, and its face is not seen; so that it may be reasonably concluded they will issue in rain, or wind, or both. ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "p",
        "class": "",
        "text": "O ye hypocrites. The Vulgate Latin, and Munster's Hebrew Gospel, leave out this appellation; but all other versions, as well as copies, have it: and it is an usual epithet, bestowed very justly by Christ, on these men; who pretended to be the guides of the people, took upon them to teach and instruct them in divine things, and set up themselves as men of great holiness, piety and knowledge; and yet, instead of searching the Scriptures, and comparing the characters of the times of the Messiah therein fixed, with the present ones, spent their time in making such low and useless observations, and which fall within the compass of everyone's knowledge and reach. ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "p",
        "class": "",
        "text": "Ye can discern the face of the sky; very distinctly, and make some very probable guesses, if not certain conclusions, what will follow, good weather or bad: ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "p",
        "class": "",
        "text": "but can ye not discern the signs of the times? or, as the Syriac reads it, \"the time\", the present time: if they had not been blind, they might easily have discerned, that the signs of the time of the Messiah's coming were upon them, and that Jesus was the Messiah; as the departure of the sceptre from Judah, the ending of Daniel's weeks, the various miracles wrought by Christ, the wickedness of the age in which they lived, the ministry of John the Baptist, and of Christ, the great flockings of the people, both to one and to the other, with divers other things which were easy to be observed by them: but they pretend this to be a very great secret. ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "p",
        "class": "",
        "text": "\"The secret of the day of death, they say (y), and the secret of the day when the king Messiah comes, who by his wisdom can find out?'' ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "p",
        "class": "",
        "text": "(y) Targum in Ecclesiastes 7.24. ",
        "children": [
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "",
            "text": "(y) Targum in ",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "verse-link",
            "text": "Ecclesiastes 7",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "",
            "text": ".24. ",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "verse-link",
            "text": "",
            "children": []
          }
        ]
      }
    ]
  },
